      ],
      "source": "https://roxburyreview.com/3247/uncategorized/a-local-history-of-landing-port-morris/"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "South of Center Street, a former railyard once housed tracks, a roundhouse, a coal transfer station, and ample working space.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        14
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://roxburyreview.com/3247/uncategorized/a-local-history-of-landing-port-morris/"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "After the Revolutionary War, Landing and Port Morris supplied iron ore and cannonballs that helped arm George Washington’s Continental Army.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        22
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://roxburyreview.com/3247/uncategorized/a-local-history-of-landing-port-morris/"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "The Morris Canal, completed in 1827, cut through Port Morris, linking the Passaic and Delaware rivers for freight transport.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        23
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.roxburylibrary.org/local-history"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Port Morris, once a subdivision of Landing, grew rapidly after the canal and iron industry boosted the local economy.",
